{"title_page": "Solar lamp", "text_new": "Lighting system composed of a [[LED lamp]], [[solar panel]]s, [[Battery (electricity)|battery]], [[charge controller]] and there may also be an [[Power inverter|inverter]]. The lamp operates on electricity from batteries, charged through the use of solar photovoltaic panel.\n\nSolar-powered household lighting can replace other light sources like candles or [[kerosene lamp]]s. Solar lamps have a lower [[operating cost]] than kerosene lamps because renewable energy from the sun is free, unlike fuel. In addition, solar lamps produce no indoor air pollution unlike kerosene lamps. However, solar lamps generally have a higher initial cost, and are weather dependent. \n\n\nSolar lamps for use in rural situations often have the capability of providing a supply of electricity for other devices, such as for charging [[Mobile phone|cell phones]]. American investors have been working towards developing a RS. 10 / unit solar lantern for replacement of kerosene lamps.<ref>{{Cite news|title = $10 solar-powered lamp to help the poor|url = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/africaandindianocean/6365124/10-solar-powered-lamp-to-help-the-poor.html|website = Telegraph.co.uk|accessdate = 2015-12-16|date = 2009-10-18|last1 = Foster|first1 = Peter}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Global Market Share by PV Technology from 1990 to 2013.svg|thumb|272px|Global market-share in terms of annual production by PV technology since 1990]]\nSome solar photovoltaics use [[Monocrystalline silicon]] or poly-crystalline silicon panels, while newer technologies have used [[thin-film solar cell]]s.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|title = How does solar power work?|url = http://www.scientificamerican.com/article/how-does-solar-power-work/|website = www.scientificamerican.com|accessdate = 2015-10-31}}</ref> Since  modern solar cells were introduced in 1954 at [[Bell labs]],<ref>{{Cite web|title = Champions of photovoltaics technology|url = http://www.renewableenergyworld.com/articles/2010/10/champions-of-photovoltaics.html|website = www.renewableenergyworld.com|accessdate = 2015-10-31}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = How do Photovoltaics Work? - NASA Science|url = https://science.nasa.gov/science-news/science-at-nasa/2002/solarcells/|website = science.nasa.gov|accessdate = 2015-10-31}}</ref> advances in [[solar cell efficiency]] at converting light into electric power, and modern manufacturing techniques combined with efficiencies of scale have led to an international [[growth of photovoltaics]].\n\nAs of 2016, LED lamps use only about 10% of the energy an incandescent lamp requires.<ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.1111/jiec.12342|title=Potential Long-Term Global Environmental Implications of Efficient Light-Source Technologies|journal=Journal of Industrial Ecology|volume=20|issue=2|page=263|year=2016|last1=Bergesen|first1=Joseph D.|last2=T\u00e4hk\u00e4m\u00f6|first2=Leena|last3=Gibon|first3=Thomas|last4=Suh|first4=Sangwon|doi-access=free}}</ref> Efficiency in production of LED lamps has led to increased adoption as an alternative to older electric lightings\n\n==Components==\nThe complete structure of a solar lamp is shown in Figure 1. \n[[File:Solar-lamp.gif|thumb|Figure 1 <ref>{{Cite web|title = Solar power use - Connect-Green|url = http://www.connect-green.com/tag/solar-power-use/|website = www.connect-green.com|accessdate = 2015-10-31}}</ref>]]\n\n===Solar panels ===\n\nMost solar panels are made out of single crystalline silicon, a [[semiconductor]] material.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|title = How do solar cells work? - Explain that Stuff|url = http://www.explainthatstuff.com/solarcells.html|website = www.explainthatstuff.com|accessdate = 2015-10-31}}</ref> A [[solar cell]] has two different layers of silicon. The lower layer has less electrons and hence has a slight positive charge due to the negative charge nature of electrons. In addition, the upper layer has more electrons and has slightly negative charge. A potential barrier is created between these two layers. \n\nWhen the stream of light particles called photons enter, they give up their energy to the atoms in the silicon. It promotes one electron from a covalent bond to a next energy level from upper layer to the lower layer.<ref name=\":0\" /> This promotion of an electron allows freer movement within the crystal which produces a current. More light shines through, more electrons move around hence more current flows between. This process is called [[Photovoltaics|photovoltaic]] and photoelectric effect.<ref name=\":1\" /> Photovoltaic systems directly convert sunlight into electricity. <ref>{{Cite web|title = Photovoltaic Systems|url = http://photovoltaics.sustainablesources.com/|website = Photovoltaic Systems|accessdate = 2015-10-31|language = en}}</ref>\n\nSolar panels are made out of layers of different materials, as you can see in Figure 2, in order of glass, encapsulate, crystalline cells, encapsulate, back sheet, junction box and lastly frame. The encapsulate keeps out moisture and contaminants which could cause problems.<ref>{{Cite journal|url = https://www.dowcorning.com/content/publishedlit/06-10028_solar-energy-the-basics.pdf|title = The Science of Solar: Solar Energy - The Basics|last = Dow Corning|date = 2009|journal = Solar Solutions|doi = |pmid = |access-date = }}</ref>\n[[File:Layers of solar panel.jpg|thumb|Figure 2 <ref>{{Cite web|title = The Solar Panel|url = https://swcphysics30.wordpress.com/2011/06/07/the-solar-panel/|website = swcphysics30|accessdate = 2015-10-31}}</ref>]]\n\n=== Battery ===\n\nA [[Battery (electricity)|battery]] is usually housed within a metal or plastic case. Inside the case are electrodes including cathodes and anodes where chemical reactions occur. A separator also exists between cathode and anode which stops the electrodes reacting together at the same time as allowing electrical charge to flow freely between the two. Lastly, the collector conducts a charge from the battery to outside.<ref>{{Cite web|title = How Batteries Work|url = http://electronics.howstuffworks.com/everyday-tech/battery2.htm|website = HowStuffWorks|accessdate = 2015-10-31}}</ref>\n\nBatteries inside solar lamps usually use gel electrolyte technology with high performance in deep discharging, in order to enable use in extreme ranges of temperature.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|title = Solar \u2013 Philips Lighting|url = http://www.lighting.philips.com/main/products/solar.html|website = www.lighting.philips.com|accessdate = 2015-10-31}}</ref> It may also use lead-acid, nickel metal hydride, nickel cadmium, or lithium.\n\nThis part of the lamp saves up energy from the solar panel and provides power when needed at night when there is no light energy available.\n\nIn general, the efficiency of photovoltaic energy conversion is limited for physical reasons. Around 24% of [[Sunlight|solar radiation]] of a long wavelength is not absorbed. 33% is heat lost to surroundings, and further losses are of approximately 15-20%. Only 23% is absorbed which means a battery is a crucial part of solar lamp.<ref>{{Cite book|title = Crystalline silicon solar cells|last = Goetzberger|first = Adolf|publisher = John Wiley&Sons|year = 1998|isbn = 978-0-471-97144-3|location = Germany|pages = 72}}</ref>\n\n=== Charge controller ===\n\nThis section controls the entire working systems to protect battery charge. It ensures, under any circumstances including extreme weather conditions with large temperature difference, the battery does not overcharge or over discharge and damage the battery even further.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|title = Solar Street Light,LED Street Light -- Anern Industry Group|url = http://www.anern.com/Application-27.html|website = www.anern.com|accessdate = 2015-10-31}}</ref>\n\nThis section also includes additional parts such as light controller, time controller, sound, temperature compensation, lighting protection, reverse polarity protection and AC transfer switches which ensure sensitive back-up loads work normally when outage occurs.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== Working principles ==\n[[File:Solar lamp mechanism.png|thumb|Figure 3 <ref>{{Citation|url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8earltsP35w|accessdate = 2015-11-01}}</ref>]]\nLED lights are used due to their high luminous efficiency and long life. Under the control of a DC charge controller, non-contact control automatically turns on the light at dark and switches off at daytime. It sometimes also combines with time controllers to set curtain time for it to automatically switch light on and off.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nAs shown in Figure 3, the chip includes microchip(R), B-, B+, S- and S+. S+ and S- are both connected to solar panels with wire, one of which has plus charge and the other minus charge. B- and B+ are attached to two batteries in this case. The light will be shown through the LED light when all of these are connected.\n\n== Benefits ==\n\nSolar lamps can be easier for customers to install and maintain as they do not require an electricity cable. Solar lamps can benefit owners with reduced maintenance cost and costs of electricity bills. Solar lamps can also be used in areas where there is no [[electrical grid]] or remote areas that lack a reliable electricity supply.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Advantages and Disadvantages of Solar Energy {{!}} GreenMatch.co.uk|url = http://www.greenmatch.co.uk/blog/2014/08/5-advantages-and-5-disadvantages-of-solar-energy|website = www.greenmatch.co.uk|accessdate = 2015-11-01|language = en-EN}}</ref> There are many stories of people with lung disease, eye deterioration, burns and sometimes even death simply because they do not have a healthy alternative to light at night.  Women have felt unsafe walking to the toilet outside after dark.  Babies are being delivered by midwives using only a candle, and students cannot study when the sun goes down for lack of light leading to increased illiteracy and perpetual poverty.  These are the realities for over 1 billion people around the globe.   Lack of lighting equates to continued poverty felt around the world.<ref>https://esperanzamarket.com/blogs/news/93744963-changemakers-spotlight-unite-to-light</ref>\nIn solar energy lamp it converts light energy into electrical energy, i.e. It is convenient to our daily life.\n\nSolar energy output is limited by weather and can be less effective if it is cloudy, wet, or winter.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Solar Power Advantages and Disadvantages|url = http://www.sepco-solarlighting.com/blog/bid/115086/Solar-Power-Advantages-and-Disadvantages|website = www.sepco-solarlighting.com|accessdate = 2015-11-01}}</ref>\n\nHouseholds switching to solar lamps from kerosene lamps also gain from health risk associated with kerosene emissions. Kerosene often has negative impacts on human lungs.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Solar-powered lamp and charger|url = https://www.britishmuseum.org/explore/highlights/highlight_objects/solar-powered_lamp__charger.aspx|website = British Museum|accessdate = 2015-11-01|language = en}}</ref>\n\nThe use of solar energy minimizes the creation pollution indoors, where kerosene have been linked to cases of health issues. However, photovoltaic panels are made out of silicon and other toxic metals including [[Lead poisoning|lead]] that can be difficult to [[Waste management|dispose]] of.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Disadvantages Of Solar Energy - Conserve Energy Future|url = http://www.conserve-energy-future.com/Disadvantages_SolarEnergy.php|website = Conserve-Energy-Future|accessdate = 2015-11-01|language = en}}</ref>\n\nThe use of solar lights improves education for students who live in households without electricity. When the nonprofit [[Unite to Light]] donated solar-lamps to schools a remote region of Kwa Zulu Natal in South Africa test scores and pass rates improved by over 30%.  The light gives students added time to study after dark.<ref>Unite To Light https://esperanzamarket.com/blogs/news/93744963-changemakers-spotlight-unite-to-light</ref>\n\nA 2017 experimental study in unelectrified areas of northern Bangladesh found that the use of solar lanterns decreased total household expenditure, increased children\u2019s home-study hours and increased school attendance. It did not however improve the children's educational achievement to any large extent.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kudo|first=Yuya|last2=Shonchoy|first2=Abu S.|last3=Takahashi|first3=Kazushi|title=Can Solar Lanterns Improve Youth Academic Performance? Experimental Evidence from Bangladesh|journal=The World Bank Economic Review|volume=33|issue=2|pages=436\u2013460|doi=10.1093/wber/lhw073|year=2017|url=http://documents.worldbank.org/curated/en/383691485359939547/pdf/WPS7954.pdf}}</ref>\n\n== Uses  ==\n\n=== Solar street light ===\n{{main|Solar street light}}\nThese lights provide a convenient and cost-effective way to light streets at night without the need of AC electrical grids for pedestrians and drivers. They may have individual panels for each lamp of a system, or may have a large central solar panel and battery bank to power multiple lamps.[[File:Solaru lantaru.jpg|thumb|right|Solar LED lantern]]\n\n=== Rural ===\n\nIn rural India, solar lamps, commonly called solar lanterns, using either LEDs or CFLs, are being used to replace kerosene lamps, candles and other cheap alternatives of lighting. Especially in areas where electricity is otherwise difficult to access, solar lamps are very useful and it also improves the quality of life.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.treehugger.com/clean-technology/cheapest-solar-lantern-a|title=nannammmaims-to-displace-kerosene-lamps.html Cheapest Solar Lantern Aims to Displace Kerosene Lamps|author=|date=|website=treehugger.com}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Renewable energy|Energy}}\n* [[Light tube]]\n* [[Liter of Light]] project\n* [[Solar device]]\n* [[Solar street light|Solar Street Lighting]]\n* [[Solar thermal collector#Evacuated tube collectors]]\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n*{{Commonscatinline|Solar lamps}}\n \n{{Photovoltaics}}\n\n[[Category:Applications of photovoltaics]]\n[[Category:Electrical systems]]\n[[Category:Energy-saving lighting]]\n[[Category:Light fixtures]]\n[[Category:Light-emitting diodes]]\n[[Category:Types of lamp]]\n[[Category:Solar-powered devices]]\n", "text_old": "{{Refimprove|date=November 2013}}\n[[File:SolarLampLuneta.JPG|thumbnail|A solar lamp in [[Rizal Park]], [[Philippines]]]]\n[[Image:Solarlight.JPG|thumb|right| A garden solar lamp]]\n[[File:Focused sun light.jpg|thumb|Magnifying glass]]\nA '''solar lamp''' also known as solar light or solar lantern, is a lighting system composed of a [[LED lamp]], [[solar panel]]s, [[Battery (electricity)|battery]], [[charge controller]] and there may also be an [[Power inverter|inverter]]. The lamp operates on electricity from batteries, charged through the use of solar photovoltaic panel.\n\nSolar-powered household lighting can replace other light sources like candles or [[kerosene lamp]]s. Solar lamps have a lower [[operating cost]] than kerosene lamps because renewable energy from the sun is free, unlike fuel. In addition, solar lamps produce no indoor air pollution unlike kerosene lamps. However, solar lamps generally have a higher initial cost, and are weather dependent. \n\n\nSolar lamps for use in rural situations often have the capability of providing a supply of electricity for other devices, such as for charging [[Mobile phone|cell phones]]. American investors have been working towards developing a RS. 10 / unit solar lantern for replacement of kerosene lamps.<ref>{{Cite news|title = $10 solar-powered lamp to help the poor|url = https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/africaandindianocean/6365124/10-solar-powered-lamp-to-help-the-poor.html|website = Telegraph.co.uk|accessdate = 2015-12-16|date = 2009-10-18|last1 = Foster|first1 = Peter}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Global Market Share by PV Technology from 1990 to 2013.svg|thumb|272px|Global market-share in terms of annual production by PV technology since 1990]]\nSome solar photovoltaics use [[Monocrystalline silicon]] or poly-crystalline silicon panels, while newer technologies have used [[thin-film solar cell]]s.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|title = How does solar power work?|url = http://www.scientificamerican.com/article/how-does-solar-power-work/|website = www.scientificamerican.com|accessdate = 2015-10-31}}</ref> Since  modern solar cells were introduced in 1954 at [[Bell labs]],<ref>{{Cite web|title = Champions of photovoltaics technology|url = http://www.renewableenergyworld.com/articles/2010/10/champions-of-photovoltaics.html|website = www.renewableenergyworld.com|accessdate = 2015-10-31}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = How do Photovoltaics Work? - NASA Science|url = https://science.nasa.gov/science-news/science-at-nasa/2002/solarcells/|website = science.nasa.gov|accessdate = 2015-10-31}}</ref> advances in [[solar cell efficiency]] at converting light into electric power, and modern manufacturing techniques combined with efficiencies of scale have led to an international [[growth of photovoltaics]].\n\nAs of 2016, LED lamps use only about 10% of the energy an incandescent lamp requires.<ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.1111/jiec.12342|title=Potential Long-Term Global Environmental Implications of Efficient Light-Source Technologies|journal=Journal of Industrial Ecology|volume=20|issue=2|page=263|year=2016|last1=Bergesen|first1=Joseph D.|last2=T\u00e4hk\u00e4m\u00f6|first2=Leena|last3=Gibon|first3=Thomas|last4=Suh|first4=Sangwon|doi-access=free}}</ref> Efficiency in production of LED lamps has led to increased adoption as an alternative to older electric lightings\n\n==Components==\nThe complete structure of a solar lamp is shown in Figure 1. \n[[File:Solar-lamp.gif|thumb|Figure 1 <ref>{{Cite web|title = Solar power use - Connect-Green|url = http://www.connect-green.com/tag/solar-power-use/|website = www.connect-green.com|accessdate = 2015-10-31}}</ref>]]\n\n===Solar panels ===\n\nMost solar panels are made out of single crystalline silicon, a [[semiconductor]] material.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|title = How do solar cells work? - Explain that Stuff|url = http://www.explainthatstuff.com/solarcells.html|website = www.explainthatstuff.com|accessdate = 2015-10-31}}</ref> A [[solar cell]] has two different layers of silicon. The lower layer has less electrons and hence has a slight positive charge due to the negative charge nature of electrons. In addition, the upper layer has more electrons and has slightly negative charge. A potential barrier is created between these two layers. \n\nWhen the stream of light particles called photons enter, they give up their energy to the atoms in the silicon. It promotes one electron from a covalent bond to a next energy level from upper layer to the lower layer.<ref name=\":0\" /> This promotion of an electron allows freer movement within the crystal which produces a current. More light shines through, more electrons move around hence more current flows between. This process is called [[Photovoltaics|photovoltaic]] and photoelectric effect.<ref name=\":1\" /> Photovoltaic systems directly convert sunlight into electricity. <ref>{{Cite web|title = Photovoltaic Systems|url = http://photovoltaics.sustainablesources.com/|website = Photovoltaic Systems|accessdate = 2015-10-31|language = en}}</ref>\n\nSolar panels are made out of layers of different materials, as you can see in Figure 2, in order of glass, encapsulate, crystalline cells, encapsulate, back sheet, junction box and lastly frame. The encapsulate keeps out moisture and contaminants which could cause problems.<ref>{{Cite journal|url = https://www.dowcorning.com/content/publishedlit/06-10028_solar-energy-the-basics.pdf|title = The Science of Solar: Solar Energy - The Basics|last = Dow Corning|date = 2009|journal = Solar Solutions|doi = |pmid = |access-date = }}</ref>\n[[File:Layers of solar panel.jpg|thumb|Figure 2 <ref>{{Cite web|title = The Solar Panel|url = https://swcphysics30.wordpress.com/2011/06/07/the-solar-panel/|website = swcphysics30|accessdate = 2015-10-31}}</ref>]]\n\n=== Battery ===\n\nA [[Battery (electricity)|battery]] is usually housed within a metal or plastic case. Inside the case are electrodes including cathodes and anodes where chemical reactions occur. A separator also exists between cathode and anode which stops the electrodes reacting together at the same time as allowing electrical charge to flow freely between the two. Lastly, the collector conducts a charge from the battery to outside.<ref>{{Cite web|title = How Batteries Work|url = http://electronics.howstuffworks.com/everyday-tech/battery2.htm|website = HowStuffWorks|accessdate = 2015-10-31}}</ref>\n\nBatteries inside solar lamps usually use gel electrolyte technology with high performance in deep discharging, in order to enable use in extreme ranges of temperature.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|title = Solar \u2013 Philips Lighting|url = http://www.lighting.philips.com/main/products/solar.html|website = www.lighting.philips.com|accessdate = 2015-10-31}}</ref> It may also use lead-acid, nickel metal hydride, nickel cadmium, or lithium.\n\nThis part of the lamp saves up energy from the solar panel and provides power when needed at night when there is no light energy available.\n\nIn general, the efficiency of photovoltaic energy conversion is limited for physical reasons. Around 24% of [[Sunlight|solar radiation]] of a long wavelength is not absorbed. 33% is heat lost to surroundings, and further losses are of approximately 15-20%. Only 23% is absorbed which means a battery is a crucial part of solar lamp.<ref>{{Cite book|title = Crystalline silicon solar cells|last = Goetzberger|first = Adolf|publisher = John Wiley&Sons|year = 1998|isbn = 978-0-471-97144-3|location = Germany|pages = 72}}</ref>\n\n=== Charge controller ===\n\nThis section controls the entire working systems to protect battery charge. It ensures, under any circumstances including extreme weather conditions with large temperature difference, the battery does not overcharge or over discharge and damage the battery even further.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|title = Solar Street Light,LED Street Light -- Anern Industry Group|url = http://www.anern.com/Application-27.html|website = www.anern.com|accessdate = 2015-10-31}}</ref>\n\nThis section also includes additional parts such as light controller, time controller, sound, temperature compensation, lighting protection, reverse polarity protection and AC transfer switches which ensure sensitive back-up loads work normally when outage occurs.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== Working principles ==\n[[File:Solar lamp mechanism.png|thumb|Figure 3 <ref>{{Citation|url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8earltsP35w|accessdate = 2015-11-01}}</ref>]]\nLED lights are used due to their high luminous efficiency and long life. Under the control of a DC charge controller, non-contact control automatically turns on the light at dark and switches off at daytime. It sometimes also combines with time controllers to set curtain time for it to automatically switch light on and off.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nAs shown in Figure 3, the chip includes microchip(R), B-, B+, S- and S+. S+ and S- are both connected to solar panels with wire, one of which has plus charge and the other minus charge. B- and B+ are attached to two batteries in this case. The light will be shown through the LED light when all of these are connected.\n\n== Benefits ==\n\nSolar lamps can be easier for customers to install and maintain as they do not require an electricity cable. Solar lamps can benefit owners with reduced maintenance cost and costs of electricity bills. Solar lamps can also be used in areas where there is no [[electrical grid]] or remote areas that lack a reliable electricity supply.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Advantages and Disadvantages of Solar Energy {{!}} GreenMatch.co.uk|url = http://www.greenmatch.co.uk/blog/2014/08/5-advantages-and-5-disadvantages-of-solar-energy|website = www.greenmatch.co.uk|accessdate = 2015-11-01|language = en-EN}}</ref> There are many stories of people with lung disease, eye deterioration, burns and sometimes even death simply because they do not have a healthy alternative to light at night.  Women have felt unsafe walking to the toilet outside after dark.  Babies are being delivered by midwives using only a candle, and students cannot study when the sun goes down for lack of light leading to increased illiteracy and perpetual poverty.  These are the realities for over 1 billion people around the globe.   Lack of lighting equates to continued poverty felt around the world.<ref>https://esperanzamarket.com/blogs/news/93744963-changemakers-spotlight-unite-to-light</ref>\nIn solar energy lamp it converts light energy into electrical energy, i.e. It is convenient to our daily life.\n\nSolar energy output is limited by weather and can be less effective if it is cloudy, wet, or winter.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Solar Power Advantages and Disadvantages|url = http://www.sepco-solarlighting.com/blog/bid/115086/Solar-Power-Advantages-and-Disadvantages|website = www.sepco-solarlighting.com|accessdate = 2015-11-01}}</ref>\n\nHouseholds switching to solar lamps from kerosene lamps also gain from health risk associated with kerosene emissions. Kerosene often has negative impacts on human lungs.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Solar-powered lamp and charger|url = https://www.britishmuseum.org/explore/highlights/highlight_objects/solar-powered_lamp__charger.aspx|website = British Museum|accessdate = 2015-11-01|language = en}}</ref>\n\nThe use of solar energy minimizes the creation pollution indoors, where kerosene have been linked to cases of health issues. However, photovoltaic panels are made out of silicon and other toxic metals including [[Lead poisoning|lead]] that can be difficult to [[Waste management|dispose]] of.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Disadvantages Of Solar Energy - Conserve Energy Future|url = http://www.conserve-energy-future.com/Disadvantages_SolarEnergy.php|website = Conserve-Energy-Future|accessdate = 2015-11-01|language = en}}</ref>\n\nThe use of solar lights improves education for students who live in households without electricity. When the nonprofit [[Unite to Light]] donated solar-lamps to schools a remote region of Kwa Zulu Natal in South Africa test scores and pass rates improved by over 30%.  The light gives students added time to study after dark.<ref>Unite To Light https://esperanzamarket.com/blogs/news/93744963-changemakers-spotlight-unite-to-light</ref>\n\nA 2017 experimental study in unelectrified areas of northern Bangladesh found that the use of solar lanterns decreased total household expenditure, increased children\u2019s home-study hours and increased school attendance. It did not however improve the children's educational achievement to any large extent.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kudo|first=Yuya|last2=Shonchoy|first2=Abu S.|last3=Takahashi|first3=Kazushi|title=Can Solar Lanterns Improve Youth Academic Performance? Experimental Evidence from Bangladesh|journal=The World Bank Economic Review|volume=33|issue=2|pages=436\u2013460|doi=10.1093/wber/lhw073|year=2017|url=http://documents.worldbank.org/curated/en/383691485359939547/pdf/WPS7954.pdf}}</ref>\n\n== Uses  ==\n\n=== Solar street light ===\n{{main|Solar street light}}\nThese lights provide a convenient and cost-effective way to light streets at night without the need of AC electrical grids for pedestrians and drivers. They may have individual panels for each lamp of a system, or may have a large central solar panel and battery bank to power multiple lamps.[[File:Solaru lantaru.jpg|thumb|right|Solar LED lantern]]\n\n=== Rural ===\n\nIn rural India, solar lamps, commonly called solar lanterns, using either LEDs or CFLs, are being used to replace kerosene lamps, candles and other cheap alternatives of lighting. Especially in areas where electricity is otherwise difficult to access, solar lamps are very useful and it also improves the quality of life.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.treehugger.com/clean-technology/cheapest-solar-lantern-a|title=nannammmaims-to-displace-kerosene-lamps.html Cheapest Solar Lantern Aims to Displace Kerosene Lamps|author=|date=|website=treehugger.com}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Renewable energy|Energy}}\n* [[Light tube]]\n* [[Liter of Light]] project\n* [[Solar device]]\n* [[Solar street light|Solar Street Lighting]]\n* [[Solar thermal collector#Evacuated tube collectors]]\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n==External links==\n*{{Commonscatinline|Solar lamps}}\n \n{{Photovoltaics}}\n\n[[Category:Applications of photovoltaics]]\n[[Category:Electrical systems]]\n[[Category:Energy-saving lighting]]\n[[Category:Light fixtures]]\n[[Category:Light-emitting diodes]]\n[[Category:Types of lamp]]\n[[Category:Solar-powered devices]]\n", "name_user": "2a02:a03f:4ccc:1900:5a8:259c:70a3:91ad", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Solar_lamp"}
{"title_page": "Stephen Lapeyrouse", "text_new": "'''Stephen Ludger Lapeyrouse''' (born December 10, 1952) is an American author, essayist, journalist and the founder of [[English Language Evenings|ELE]] community-forum in Moscow, Russia. \n        \n==Biography==\nStephen Lapeyrouse was born in [[Fort Knox]], Kentucky; grew up in [[Mobile, Alabama|Mobile]], Alabama. Graduated University Military School in 1971; graduated New College, [[University of Alabama]] in 1977 with a [[Bachelor of Arts|BA]] in Interdisciplinary Studies: Religion and Philosophy; he received an [[Master of Arts|MA]] in 1981 with [[Antioch College]]\u2019s Individualized Master of Arts Degree Program (resided in Germany and Switzerland), completed his Master\u2019s Thesis, \u201cIn Quest of Incarnation\u201d, in the [[San Francisco Bay Area]].\n\nIn 1988-89 Lapeyrouse delivered a series of public lectures titled \"Chrysopylae Lectures \u2013 The Call of Spiritual Nobility\", in [[Santa Cruz, California|Santa Cruz]], [[Palo Alto, California|Palo Alto]], [[Berkeley, California|Berkeley]], and [[Mount Shasta, California|Mt Shasta]], California.<ref>{{cite web|title= Chrysopylae Lectures \u2013 The Call of Spiritual Nobility|url=http://www.americanreflections.net/essays/the_chrysopylae_lectures_the_call_of_spiritual_nobility_en.html }}</ref>\n\nAfter annual travels to [[Russia]] starting in 1986 he wrote a book ''Towards the Spiritual Convergence of America and Russia: American Mind and Russian Soul, American Individuality and Russian Community, and the Potent Alchemy of National Characteristics'' (published in Santa Cruz, 1990).\n\nLapeyrouse moved to [[Moscow]] in July 1994.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.themoscowtimes.com/news/article/up-close-russia-is-worth-wait-for-us-philosopher/290208.html|title= UP CLOSE: Russia Is Worth Wait for U.S. Philosopher|work= The Moscow Times|date= May 27, 1998}}</ref>\n\nIn 1994 he won the prize (shared with Tatyana Morozova) of the literary magazine ''[[Moskva (magazine)|Moskva]]''<ref>{{cite web|title=\u041f\u0440\u0435\u043c\u0438\u0438 \u0436\u0443\u0440\u043d\u0430\u043b\u0430 ''\u041c\u043e\u0441\u043a\u0432\u0430'' \u2013 1994|url=http://www.rsl.ru/datadocs/doc_7094fo.pdf}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.americanreflections.net/interviews/interview_severnaya_stolitsa_28(44)_1995_ru.html|title=\u0418\u043d\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0432\u044c\u044e \u0441\u043e \u0421\u0442\u0438\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043e\u043c \u041b\u0430\u043f\u0435\u0440\u0443\u0437\u043e\u043c. \u0414\u043c\u0438\u0442\u0440\u0438\u0439 \u0411\u0430\u0434\u0430\u043b\u044f\u043d. \u041f\u043e \u0442\u0443 \u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u043e\u043d\u0443 \u043e\u043a\u0435\u0430\u043d\u0430.|work= \u0421\u0435\u0432\u0435\u0440\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0441\u0442\u043e\u043b\u0438\u0446\u0430|date= 25-31 \u0430\u0432\u0433\u0443\u0441\u0442\u0430 1995 \u0433.}}</ref> for the first article in the series \u201cRussian-American Dialogue\u201d;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.americanreflections.net/interviews_ru.html#dialogue|title=\u0421\u0435\u0440\u0438\u044f \u043f\u0443\u0431\u043b\u0438\u043a\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0439 \u0421\u0442\u0438\u0432\u0435\u043d\u0430 \u041b\u0430\u043f\u0435\u0440\u0443\u0437\u0430 \u0438 \u0422\u0430\u0442\u044c\u044f\u043d\u044b \u041c\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0437\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0439 \"\u0420\u0443\u0441\u0441\u043a\u043e-\u0430\u043c\u0435\u0440\u0438\u043a\u0430\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0434\u0438\u0430\u043b\u043e\u0433\"|work= \u041c\u043e\u0441\u043a\u0432\u0430|date= 1994-1998 \u0433\u0433.}}</ref> participated in a round-table discussion on Russia with [[Aleksandr Solzhenitsyn]] at the ''Moskva'' office on [[Arbat Street]] in 1998.\n\nSince 1995 Lapeyrouse worked as a writer, editor and consultant for the educational magazine ''English''<ref>{{cite web|title= English magazine|url= http://eng.1september.ru/}}</ref> of Publishing House \u201cFirst of September\u201d. With some TV appearances over the years, during 2013 he was a special correspondent for eighteen programs of \u201cBrainstorm\u201d on [[TV Tsentr]];<ref>{{cite web|title= \u0421\u0442\u0438\u0432\u0435\u043d \u041b\u0430\u043f\u0435\u0440\u0443\u0437 \u2013 \u0441\u043f\u0435\u0446\u0438\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u043a\u043e\u0440\u0440\u0435\u0441\u043f\u043e\u043d\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0442 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0433\u0440\u0430\u043c\u043c\u044b \"\u041c\u043e\u0437\u0433\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0439 \u0448\u0442\u0443\u0440\u043c\"|url= http://mozgovoyshturm.ru/info/comand/}}</ref> and has been a free-lance contributor to various periodicals since 1994.\n\nIn 1998 he founded an independent, public English-language lecture forum [[English Language Evenings]] (ELE) to which he remained host and moderator until 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.themoscowtimes.com/news/article/riddle-wrapped-in-english-debate/264961.html|title= Riddle Wrapped in English Debate|work= The Moscow Times|date= March 28, 2000}}</ref> ELE has had more than 250 meetings with more than 200 different speakers from some 12 different countries since it began.\n\nIn summer 2013 Lapeyrouse read passages from [[Henry David Thoreau|HenryThoreau]]'s ''[[Walden]]'' at the inauguration ceremony of the Thoreau Cabin in the Russian village of Medvedevo during the annual meeting of the Ugory Project.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.ugory.ru/news.htm|title=\u0423\u0433\u043e\u0440\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0435\u043a\u0442 \u2013 \u041d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013 Stephen Lapeyrouse became one of the nominees for ''[[The Moscow News]]'' special prize \u201cImport of Goodwill\u201d honoring expats who perform community service for public benefit in Russia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.americanreflections.net/interviews/interview_moscow_news_27_november_2013_en.html |title=Import of Goodwill: An engine of ideas on Pushkin Square |work= The Moscow News|date=November 27, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n* ''Towards the Spiritual Convergence of America and Russia: American Mind and Russian Soul, American Individuality and Russian Community, and the Potent Alchemy of National Characteristics'', 1990. \u2013 {{ISBN|0-9628048-0-0}}<ref>{{cite web|title= Towards the Spiritual Convergence of America and Russia (first published in 1990) \u2013 free download page|url=http://www.americanreflections.net/books_en.html}}</ref>\n* ''\u0412 \u043f\u043e\u0438\u0441\u043a\u0430\u0445 \u00ab\u0410\u043c\u0435\u0440\u0438\u043a\u0430\u043d\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u043c\u0435\u0447\u0442\u044b\u00bb \u2013 \u0418\u0437\u0431\u0440\u0430\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u044d\u0441\u0441\u0435'', M.: \u0411\u0443\u043a\u0438 \u0412\u0435\u0434\u0438, 2015. \u2013 {{ISBN|978-5-4465-0687-3}}<ref>{{cite web|title= \u0412 \u043f\u043e\u0438\u0441\u043a\u0430\u0445 \u00ab\u0410\u043c\u0435\u0440\u0438\u043a\u0430\u043d\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u043c\u0435\u0447\u0442\u044b\u00bb \u2013 \u0418\u0437\u0431\u0440\u0430\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u044d\u0441\u0441\u0435 (2015) \u2013 free download page|url=http://www.americanreflections.net/books_en.html#sad}}</ref>  \nPeriodical publications (selection from 80+ articles 1995-2007)<ref>{{cite web|title= The complete list of Stephen Lapeyrouse\u2019s periodical publications|url=http://www.americanreflections.net/essays_en.html}}</ref>\n* ''The Search for the \u201cAmerican Dream\u201d'' (5 parts; ''English'', October \u2013 November 1995)<ref>{{cite web|title=The Search for the \"American Dream\" (1995)|url=http://www.americanreflections.net/essays/the_search_for_the_american_dream_en.html}}</ref>\n* ''Notes on the Lost Cosmos of American Culture'' (17 parts; ''English'', November 1995 \u2013 August 1996)<ref>{{cite web|title=Notes on the Lost Cosmos of American Culture (1996)|url=http://www.americanreflections.net/essays/notes_on_the_lost_cosmos_en.html}}</ref>\n* ''Worried Questions to Russian Teenagers, from an American Scholar'' (''English'', No. 5, February 1997)<ref>{{cite web|title=Worried Questions to Russian Teenagers, from an American Scholar (1997)|url=http://www.americanreflections.net/essays/worried_questions_to_russian_teenagers_from_an_american_scholar_en.html}}</ref>\n* ''Contrasting Ideas of Man \u2013 The \u201cAmerican Creed\u201d vs. the \u201cPerennial Philosophy\u201d'' (\u0410\u043c\u0435\u0440\u0438\u043a\u0430\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0445\u0430\u0440\u0430\u043a\u0442\u0435\u0440. \u0422\u0440\u0430\u0434\u0438\u0446\u0438\u044f \u0432 \u043a\u0443\u043b\u044c\u0442\u0443\u0440\u0435: \u041e\u0447\u0435\u0440\u043a\u0438 \u043a\u0443\u043b\u044c\u0442\u0443\u0440\u044b \u0421\u0428\u0410 / \u043e\u0442\u0432. \u0440\u0435\u0434. \u041e.\u042d. \u0422\u0443\u0433\u0430\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0430. \u2013 \u041c.: \u041d\u0430\u0443\u043a\u0430, 1998. \u2013 \u0421. 68-98.)<ref>{{cite web|title=Contrasting Ideas of Man \u2013 The \u2018American Creed\u2019 vs. the \u2018Perennial Philosophy\u2019 (1998)|url=http://www.americanreflections.net/essays/contrasting_ideas_of_man_en.html}}</ref>\n* ''Zarathustra\u2019s Answer to Leo Tolstoy\u2019s Despair'' (''English'', No. 22, June 1999)<ref>{{cite web|title=Zarathustra\u2019s Answer to Leo Tolstoy\u2019s Despair (1999)|url=http://www.americanreflections.net/essays/zarathustra_answer_to_leo_tolstoy_despair_en.html}}</ref>\n* ''\u201cGazing on the face of death...\u201d \u2013 The Memento Mori of \u201cSeptember 11, 2001\u201d'' (''English'', No. 34, September 2002)<ref>{{cite web|title=\u201cGazing on the face of death...\u201d \u2013 The Memento Mori of \u201cSeptember 11, 2001\u201d (2002)|url=http://www.americanreflections.net/essays/gazing_in_the_face_of_death_en.html}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.americanreflections.net/  Stephen Lapeyrouse\u2019s personal website ''an American's Reflections'']\n* [http://elemoscow.net/index.html  ELE official website]\n* [http://www.passportmagazine.ru/article/1592/ How to Get a Residence Permit II] ''Passport Moscow'' (July, 2009)\n* [http://www.passportmagazine.ru/article/1786/  Third Round to Stephen Lapeyrouse] ''Passport Moscow'' (February, 2010)\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lapeyrouse, Stephen}}\n[[Category:1952 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American male writers]]\n", "text_old": "'''Stephen Ludger Lapeyrouse''' (born December 10, 1952) is an American author, essayist, journalist and the founder of [[English Language Evenings|ELE]] community-forum in Moscow, Russia. \n        \n==Biography==\nStephen Lapeyrouse was born in [[Fort Knox]], Kentucky; grew up in [[Mobile, Alabama|Mobile]], Alabama. Graduated University Military School in 1971; graduated New College, [[University of Alabama]] in 1977 with a [[Bachelor of Arts|BA]] in Interdisciplinary Studies: Religion and Philosophy; he received an [[Master of Arts|MA]] in 1981 with [[Antioch College]]\u2019s Individualized Master of Arts Degree Program (resided in Germany and Switzerland), completed his Master\u2019s Thesis, \u201cIn Quest of Incarnation\u201d, in the [[San Francisco Bay Area]].\n\nIn 1988-89 Lapeyrouse delivered a series of public lectures titled \"Chrysopylae Lectures \u2013 The Call of Spiritual Nobility\", in [[Santa Cruz, California|Santa Cruz]], [[Palo Alto, California|Palo Alto]], [[Berkeley, California|Berkeley]], and [[Mount Shasta, California|Mt Shasta]], California.<ref>{{cite web|title= Chrysopylae Lectures \u2013 The Call of Spiritual Nobility|url=http://www.americanreflections.net/essays/the_chrysopylae_lectures_the_call_of_spiritual_nobility_en.html }}</ref>\n\nAfter annual travels to [[Russia]] starting in 1986 he wrote a book ''Towards the Spiritual Convergence of America and Russia: American Mind and Russian Soul, American Individuality and Russian Community, and the Potent Alchemy of National Characteristics'' (published in Santa Cruz, 1990).\n\nLapeyrouse moved to [[Moscow]] in July 1994.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.themoscowtimes.com/news/article/up-close-russia-is-worth-wait-for-us-philosopher/290208.html|title= UP CLOSE: Russia Is Worth Wait for U.S. Philosopher|work= The Moscow Times|date= May 27, 1998}}</ref>\n\nIn 1994 he won the prize (shared with Tatyana Morozova) of the literary magazine ''[[Moskva (magazine)|Moskva]]''<ref>{{cite web|title=\u041f\u0440\u0435\u043c\u0438\u0438 \u0436\u0443\u0440\u043d\u0430\u043b\u0430 ''\u041c\u043e\u0441\u043a\u0432\u0430'' \u2013 1994|url=http://www.rsl.ru/datadocs/doc_7094fo.pdf}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.americanreflections.net/interviews/interview_severnaya_stolitsa_28(44)_1995_ru.html|title=\u0418\u043d\u0442\u0435\u0440\u0432\u044c\u044e \u0441\u043e \u0421\u0442\u0438\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043e\u043c \u041b\u0430\u043f\u0435\u0440\u0443\u0437\u043e\u043c. \u0414\u043c\u0438\u0442\u0440\u0438\u0439 \u0411\u0430\u0434\u0430\u043b\u044f\u043d. \u041f\u043e \u0442\u0443 \u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u043e\u043d\u0443 \u043e\u043a\u0435\u0430\u043d\u0430.|work= \u0421\u0435\u0432\u0435\u0440\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0441\u0442\u043e\u043b\u0438\u0446\u0430|date= 25-31 \u0430\u0432\u0433\u0443\u0441\u0442\u0430 1995 \u0433.}}</ref> for the first article in the series \u201cRussian-American Dialogue\u201d;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.americanreflections.net/interviews_ru.html#dialogue|title=\u0421\u0435\u0440\u0438\u044f \u043f\u0443\u0431\u043b\u0438\u043a\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0439 \u0421\u0442\u0438\u0432\u0435\u043d\u0430 \u041b\u0430\u043f\u0435\u0440\u0443\u0437\u0430 \u0438 \u0422\u0430\u0442\u044c\u044f\u043d\u044b \u041c\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0437\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0439 \"\u0420\u0443\u0441\u0441\u043a\u043e-\u0430\u043c\u0435\u0440\u0438\u043a\u0430\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0434\u0438\u0430\u043b\u043e\u0433\"|work= \u041c\u043e\u0441\u043a\u0432\u0430|date= 1994-1998 \u0433\u0433.}}</ref> participated in a round-table discussion on Russia with [[Aleksandr Solzhenitsyn]] at the ''Moskva'' office on [[Arbat Street]] in 1998.\n\nSince 1995 Lapeyrouse worked as a writer, editor and consultant for the educational magazine ''English''<ref>{{cite web|title= English magazine|url= http://eng.1september.ru/}}</ref> of Publishing House \u201cFirst of September\u201d. With some TV appearances over the years, during 2013 he was a special correspondent for eighteen programs of \u201cBrainstorm\u201d on [[TV Tsentr]];<ref>{{cite web|title= \u0421\u0442\u0438\u0432\u0435\u043d \u041b\u0430\u043f\u0435\u0440\u0443\u0437 \u2013 \u0441\u043f\u0435\u0446\u0438\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u043a\u043e\u0440\u0440\u0435\u0441\u043f\u043e\u043d\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0442 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0433\u0440\u0430\u043c\u043c\u044b \"\u041c\u043e\u0437\u0433\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0439 \u0448\u0442\u0443\u0440\u043c\"|url= http://mozgovoyshturm.ru/info/comand/}}</ref> and has been a free-lance contributor to various periodicals since 1994.\n\nIn 1998 he founded an independent, public English-language lecture forum [[English Language Evenings]] (ELE) to which he remained host and moderator until 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.themoscowtimes.com/news/article/riddle-wrapped-in-english-debate/264961.html|title= Riddle Wrapped in English Debate|work= The Moscow Times|date= March 28, 2000}}</ref> ELE has had more than 250 meetings with more than 200 different speakers from some 12 different countries since it began.\n\nIn summer 2013 Lapeyrouse read passages from [[Henry David Thoreau|HenryThoreau]]'s ''[[Walden]]'' at the inauguration ceremony of the Thoreau Cabin in the Russian village of Medvedevo during the annual meeting of the Ugory Project.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.ugory.ru/news.htm|title=\u0423\u0433\u043e\u0440\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0435\u043a\u0442 \u2013 \u041d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013 Stephen Lapeyrouse became one of the nominees for ''[[The Moscow News]]'' special prize \u201cImport of Goodwill\u201d honoring expats who perform community service for public benefit in Russia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.americanreflections.net/interviews/interview_moscow_news_27_november_2013_en.html |title=Import of Goodwill: An engine of ideas on Pushkin Square |work= The Moscow News|date=November 27, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Bibliography==\n* ''Towards the Spiritual Convergence of America and Russia: American Mind and Russian Soul, American Individuality and Russian Community, and the Potent Alchemy of National Characteristics'', 1990. \u2013 {{ISBN|0-9628048-0-0}}<ref>{{cite web|title= Towards the Spiritual Convergence of America and Russia (first published in 1990) \u2013 free download page|url=http://www.americanreflections.net/books_en.html}}</ref>\n* ''\u0412 \u043f\u043e\u0438\u0441\u043a\u0430\u0445 \u00ab\u0410\u043c\u0435\u0440\u0438\u043a\u0430\u043d\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u043c\u0435\u0447\u0442\u044b\u00bb \u2013 \u0418\u0437\u0431\u0440\u0430\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u044d\u0441\u0441\u0435'', M.: \u0411\u0443\u043a\u0438 \u0412\u0435\u0434\u0438, 2015. \u2013 {{ISBN|978-5-4465-0687-3}}<ref>{{cite web|title= \u0412 \u043f\u043e\u0438\u0441\u043a\u0430\u0445 \u00ab\u0410\u043c\u0435\u0440\u0438\u043a\u0430\u043d\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u043c\u0435\u0447\u0442\u044b\u00bb \u2013 \u0418\u0437\u0431\u0440\u0430\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u044d\u0441\u0441\u0435 (2015) \u2013 free download page|url=http://www.americanreflections.net/books_en.html#sad}}</ref>  \nPeriodical publications (selection from 80+ articles 1995-2007)<ref>{{cite web|title= The complete list of Stephen Lapeyrouse\u2019s periodical publications|url=http://www.americanreflections.net/essays_en.html}}</ref>\n* ''The Search for the \u201cAmerican Dream\u201d'' (5 parts; ''English'', October \u2013 November 1995)<ref>{{cite web|title=The Search for the \"American Dream\" (1995)|url=http://www.americanreflections.net/essays/the_search_for_the_american_dream_en.html}}</ref>\n* ''Notes on the Lost Cosmos of American Culture'' (17 parts; ''English'', November 1995 \u2013 August 1996)<ref>{{cite web|title=Notes on the Lost Cosmos of American Culture (1996)|url=http://www.americanreflections.net/essays/notes_on_the_lost_cosmos_en.html}}</ref>\n* ''Worried Questions to Russian Teenagers, from an American Scholar'' (''English'', No. 5, February 1997)<ref>{{cite web|title=Worried Questions to Russian Teenagers, from an American Scholar (1997)|url=http://www.americanreflections.net/essays/worried_questions_to_russian_teenagers_from_an_american_scholar_en.html}}</ref>\n* ''Contrasting Ideas of Man \u2013 The \u201cAmerican Creed\u201d vs. the \u201cPerennial Philosophy\u201d'' (\u0410\u043c\u0435\u0440\u0438\u043a\u0430\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0445\u0430\u0440\u0430\u043a\u0442\u0435\u0440. \u0422\u0440\u0430\u0434\u0438\u0446\u0438\u044f \u0432 \u043a\u0443\u043b\u044c\u0442\u0443\u0440\u0435: \u041e\u0447\u0435\u0440\u043a\u0438 \u043a\u0443\u043b\u044c\u0442\u0443\u0440\u044b \u0421\u0428\u0410 / \u043e\u0442\u0432. \u0440\u0435\u0434. \u041e.\u042d. \u0422\u0443\u0433\u0430\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0430. \u2013 \u041c.: \u041d\u0430\u0443\u043a\u0430, 1998. \u2013 \u0421. 68-98.)<ref>{{cite web|title=Contrasting Ideas of Man \u2013 The \u2018American Creed\u2019 vs. the \u2018Perennial Philosophy\u2019 (1998)|url=http://www.americanreflections.net/essays/contrasting_ideas_of_man_en.html}}</ref>\n* ''Zarathustra\u2019s Answer to Leo Tolstoy\u2019s Despair'' (''English'', No. 22, June 1999)<ref>{{cite web|title=Zarathustra\u2019s Answer to Leo Tolstoy\u2019s Despair (1999)|url=http://www.americanreflections.net/essays/zarathustra_answer_to_leo_tolstoy_despair_en.html}}</ref>\n* ''\u201cGazing on the face of death...\u201d \u2013 The Memento Mori of \u201cSeptember 11, 2001\u201d'' (''English'', No. 34, September 2002)<ref>{{cite web|title=\u201cGazing on the face of death...\u201d \u2013 The Memento Mori of \u201cSeptember 11, 2001\u201d (2002)|url=http://www.americanreflections.net/essays/gazing_in_the_face_of_death_en.html}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.americanreflections.net/  Stephen Lapeyrouse\u2019s personal website ''an American's Reflections'']\n* [http://elemoscow.net/index.html  ELE official website]\n* [http://www.passportmagazine.ru/article/1592/ How to Get a Residence Permit II] ''Passport Moscow'' (July, 2009)\n* [http://www.passportmagazine.ru/article/1786/  Third Round to Stephen Lapeyrouse] ''Passport Moscow'' (February, 2010)\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lapeyrouse, Stephen}}\n[[Category:1952 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American male writers]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stephen_Lapeyrouse"}
{"title_page": "TSLAQ", "text_new": "{{POV|date=April 2020}}\n{{third-party|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date = November 2019}}\n{{Infobox organization\n| name = TSLAQ\n| native_name = $TSLAQ\n| image = [[File:TslaQ-no-tag.png]]\n| nickname = TESLAQ\n| named_after = Tesla [[Ticker Symbol]] + \"Q\" which is the [[Chapter 11, Title 11, United States Code#Stock|NASDAQ notation for bankruptcy]]\n| formation = {{start date and age|Oct. 7, 2015}}\n| type = Anti-[[Tesla, Inc.|Tesla]], [[Networked advocacy]], [[fraud deterrence]], [[Short (finance)|Pro-Shorting]]\n| origins = Twitter\n| region = International\n| key_people = Lawrence Fossi, @TESLAcharts, @Paul91701736, [[Martin Tripp]]\n| website = https://www.tslaq.org\n}}\n'''TSLAQ''' is a loosely-collected group of largely anonymous<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/02/01/tesla-shorts-who-take-aerial-pictures-of-parking-lots-launch-web-site.html|title=Anonymous Tesla short sellers who fly over its parking lots taking pictures of cars have a new web site|last=Kolodny|first=Lora|date=2019-02-01|website=CNBC|language=en|access-date=2019-11-07}}</ref> [[Tesla, Inc.]] [[short-seller]]s and other individuals critical of [[Elon Musk]] and aspects of Tesla who primarily organize on [[Twitter]]<ref name=\"mitchell\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/business/autos/la-fi-hy-tesla-short-sellers-musk-20190408-story.html|title=Must Reads: The crowd-sourced, social media swarm that is betting Tesla will crash and burn|last=Mitchell|first=Russ|date=2019-04-08|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-07}}</ref> and [[Reddit]]<ref name=\"wired\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/elon-musk-twitter-fans|title=Inside the obsessive Twitter turf war over Elon Musk's Tesla tweets|last=Katwalla|first=Amit|date=May 5, 2019|work=Wired|access-date=December 19, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> in order to share news, openly discuss matters concerning the company and its stock, and coordinate efforts.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/features/2020-01-22/the-tesla-tslaq-skeptics-who-bet-against-elon-musk|title=The Tesla sceptics who bet against Elon Musk|last=|first=|date=2020-01-22|website=Bloomberg|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> Edward Niedermeyer, author of ''Ludicrous: The Unvarnished Story of Tesla Motors'', establishes the [[Doxing|doxxing]] of Lawrence Fossi, a [[Seeking Alpha]] writer and Tesla short seller, as \"catalyz[ing] th[e] loose association of individuals... some of whom were pure financial speculators [...] and others who were motivated by factors other than money.\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=Ludicrous: The Unvarnished Story of Tesla Motors|last=Niedermeyer|first=Edward|publisher=BenBella Books, Incorporated|year=2019|isbn=9781948836326|location=|pages=125}}</ref> The group was the subject of a Real Vision video which included interviews with prominent members @TESLACharts and @Paul91701736.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.realvision.com/tv/shows/the-big-story/videos/tesla-electric-noise|title=Tesla: Electric Noise|last=|first=|date=March 27, 2019|website=Real Vision|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=January 16, 2020}}</ref>  \n\nThe group at times exchanges online verbal hostilities with Tesla fans<ref name=\"wired\" /> and Elon Musk has [[Twitter#Tweets|tweeted]] with a prominent member.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/elonmusk/status/1008404147584921600|title=How big is your short position? Just curious.|last=Musk|first=Elon|date=2018-06-17|website=twitter.com/elonmusk|language=en|access-date=2019-09-07}}</ref> \n{{TOC limit}}\n\n== Hothi Allegations & Crowdfunding ==\n\nIn April 2019, Tesla filed a lawsuit and a request for a restraining order against TSLAQ member, Randeep Hothi also known as @skabooshka.<ref name=\":0\" /> The allegations spanned two episodes:\n\n# In February 2019, Mr. Hothi was found sitting in his car in the Tesla Fremont Factory parking lot. Security ordered him to leave at which point Tesla alleges he exited at high speed and nearly struck an employee.<ref name=\":1\" />\n# In a separate instance in April 2019, Mr. Hothi spotted a Tesla on the highway fitted with numerous camera systems and personnel in the car and he proceeded to film the vehicle believing it to be demonstrating and filming Tesla's [[Tesla Autopilot|Autopilot]] capabilities. Tesla alleges that he drove erratically and dangerously.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/tesla-drops-suit-against-shortseller-hothi-refuses-discovery-2019-7|title=Tesla Drops Suit Against Shortseller|last=Lopez|first=Linette|date=July 22, 2019|website=Business Insider|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=February 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn response to the allegations, using [[GoFundMe]], TSLAQ members led by Fossi ran a campaign for and contributed to the defense fund, which accrued in excess of US$100,000. The allegations and the request for a temporary restraining order against Hothi were eventually dropped by Tesla after the company refused to produce footage from within the test car to substantiate their claims. After reviewing the surveillance camera footage of Tesla parking lot from the day in question, [[Fremont, California|Fremont]] police declined to press charges.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2019/7/22/20699573/tesla-lawsuit-skabooshka-randeep-hothi-restraining-order|title=Tesla drops lawsuit against critic after judge asks for evidence|last=O'Kane|first=Sean|date=July 22, 2019|website=The Verge|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-29}}</ref>\n\n== Beliefs ==\n\nSome members short Tesla stock as they believe it will lower in value in the future; Tesla is currently the most shorted stock in 2020, with over $14.3 billion in shorted share value at its peak.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://markets.businessinsider.com/news/stocks/tesla-stock-most-shorted-us-beats-apple-highest-short-interest-2020-1-1028823046|title=Tesla just became the most shorted stock in the US, again (TSLA)|last=Reinicke|first=Carmen|date=January 16, 2020|website=Market Insider|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> As per Business Insider, members \"exchange research, news articles, and sometimes outlandish conspiracy theories about the company\" and \"[are] betting on the company\u2019s death and have found much success in irritating the billionaire executive.\"<ref name=\"businessinsider\">{{Cite web|url=https://markets.businessinsider.com/news/stocks/tesla-stock-price-twitter-musk-fans-bears-2019-4-1028119078|title=Inside Tesla Twitter|last=Ungarino|first=Rebecca|date=April 17, 2019|website=Market Insider|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=December 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the LA Times, members believe Tesla is a fraudulent company and its stock will eventually crash. Their self-reported main goal is to \"change the mind of Tesla stock bulls and the media.\" Claims against Elon Musk and Tesla include that Tesla has reached a cliff in demand and that Tesla is distorting its sales numbers of cars.<ref name=\"mitchell\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}} \n[[Category:Social movements]]\n[[Category:Internet activism]]\n", "text_old": "{{POV|date=April 2020}}\n{{third-party|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date = November 2019}}\n{{Infobox organization\n| name = TSLAQ\n| native_name = $TSLAQ\n| image = [[File:TslaQ-no-tag.png]]\n| nickname = TESLAQ\n| named_after = Tesla [[Ticker Symbol]] + \"Q\" which is the [[Chapter 11, Title 11, United States Code#Stock|NASDAQ notation for bankruptcy]]\n| formation = {{start date and age|Oct. 7, 2015}}\n| type = Anti-[[Tesla, Inc.|Tesla]], [[Networked advocacy]], [[fraud deterrence]], [[Short (finance)|Pro-Shorting]]\n| origins = Twitter\n| region = International\n| key_people = Lawrence Fossi, @TESLAcharts, @Paul91701736, [[Martin Tripp]]\n| website = https://www.tslaq.org\n}}\n'''TSLAQ''' is a loosely-collected group of largely anonymous<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/02/01/tesla-shorts-who-take-aerial-pictures-of-parking-lots-launch-web-site.html|title=Anonymous Tesla short sellers who fly over its parking lots taking pictures of cars have a new web site|last=Kolodny|first=Lora|date=2019-02-01|website=CNBC|language=en|access-date=2019-11-07}}</ref> [[Tesla, Inc.]] [[short-seller]]s and other individuals critical of [[Elon Musk]] and aspects of Tesla who primarily organize on [[Twitter]]<ref name=\"mitchell\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/business/autos/la-fi-hy-tesla-short-sellers-musk-20190408-story.html|title=Must Reads: The crowd-sourced, social media swarm that is betting Tesla will crash and burn|last=Mitchell|first=Russ|date=2019-04-08|website=Los Angeles Times|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-07}}</ref> and [[Reddit]]<ref name=\"wired\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/elon-musk-twitter-fans|title=Inside the obsessive Twitter turf war over Elon Musk's Tesla tweets|last=Katwalla|first=Amit|date=May 5, 2019|work=Wired|access-date=December 19, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> in order to share news, openly discuss matters concerning the company and its stock, and coordinate efforts.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/features/2020-01-22/the-tesla-tslaq-skeptics-who-bet-against-elon-musk|title=The Tesla sceptics who bet against Elon Musk|last=|first=|date=2020-01-22|website=Bloomberg|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-12}}</ref> Edward Niedermeyer, author of ''Ludicrous: The Unvarnished Story of Tesla Motors'', establishes the [[Doxing|doxxing]] of Lawrence Fossi, a [[Seeking Alpha]] writer and Tesla short seller, as \"catalyz[ing] th[e] loose association of individuals... some of whom were pure financial speculators [...] and others who were motivated by factors other than money.\"<ref>{{Cite book|title=Ludicrous: The Unvarnished Story of Tesla Motors|last=Niedermeyer|first=Edward|publisher=BenBella Books, Incorporated|year=2019|isbn=9781948836326|location=|pages=125}}</ref> The group was the subject of a Real Vision video which included interviews with prominent members @TESLACharts and @Paul91701736.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.realvision.com/tv/shows/the-big-story/videos/tesla-electric-noise|title=Tesla: Electric Noise|last=|first=|date=March 27, 2019|website=Real Vision|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=January 16, 2020}}</ref>  \n\nThe group at times exchanges online verbal hostilities with Tesla fans<ref name=\"wired\" /> and Elon Musk has [[Twitter#Tweets|tweeted]] with a prominent member.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/elonmusk/status/1008404147584921600|title=How big is your short position? Just curious.|last=Musk|first=Elon|date=2018-06-17|website=twitter.com/elonmusk|language=en|access-date=2019-09-07}}</ref> \n{{TOC limit}}\n\n== Hothi Allegations & Crowdfunding ==\n\nIn April 2019, Tesla filed a lawsuit and a request for a restraining order against TSLAQ member, Randeep Hothi also known as @skabooshka.<ref name=\":0\" /> The allegations spanned two episodes:\n\n# In February 2019, Mr. Hothi was found sitting in his car in the Tesla Fremont Factory parking lot. Security ordered him to leave at which point Tesla alleges he exited at high speed and nearly struck an employee.<ref name=\":1\" />\n# In a separate instance in April 2019, Mr. Hothi spotted a Tesla on the highway fitted with numerous camera systems and personnel in the car and he proceeded to film the vehicle believing it to be demonstrating and filming Tesla's [[Tesla Autopilot|Autopilot]] capabilities. Tesla alleges that he drove erratically and dangerously.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/tesla-drops-suit-against-shortseller-hothi-refuses-discovery-2019-7|title=Tesla Drops Suit Against Shortseller|last=Lopez|first=Linette|date=July 22, 2019|website=Business Insider|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=February 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn response to the allegations, using [[GoFundMe]], TSLAQ members led by Fossi ran a campaign for and contributed to the defense fund, which accrued in excess of US$100,000. The allegations and the request for a temporary restraining order against Hothi were eventually dropped by Tesla after the company refused to produce footage from within the test car to substantiate their claims. After reviewing the surveillance camera footage of Tesla parking lot from the day in question, [[Fremont, California|Fremont]] police declined to press charges.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2019/7/22/20699573/tesla-lawsuit-skabooshka-randeep-hothi-restraining-order|title=Tesla drops lawsuit against critic after judge asks for evidence|last=O'Kane|first=Sean|date=July 22, 2019|website=The Verge|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-29}}</ref>\nfun== Beliefs ==\nSome members short Tesla stock as they believe it will lower in value in the future; Tesla is currently the most shorted stock in 2020, with over $14.3 billion in shorted share value at its peak.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://markets.businessinsider.com/news/stocks/tesla-stock-most-shorted-us-beats-apple-highest-short-interest-2020-1-1028823046|title=Tesla just became the most shorted stock in the US, again (TSLA)|last=Reinicke|first=Carmen|date=January 16, 2020|website=Market Insider|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> As per Business Insider, members \"exchange research, news articles, and sometimes outlandish conspiracy theories about the company\" and \"[are] betting on the company\u2019s death and have found much success in irritating the billionaire executive.\"<ref name=\"businessinsider\">{{Cite web|url=https://markets.businessinsider.com/news/stocks/tesla-stock-price-twitter-musk-fans-bears-2019-4-1028119078|title=Inside Tesla Twitter|last=Ungarino|first=Rebecca|date=April 17, 2019|website=Market Insider|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=December 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the LA Times, members believe Tesla is a fraudulent company and its stock will eventually crash. Their self-reported main goal is to \"change the mind of Tesla stock bulls and the media.\" Claims against Elon Musk and Tesla include that Tesla has reached a cliff in demand and that Tesla is distorting its sales numbers of cars.<ref name=\"mitchell\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}} \n[[Category:Social movements]]\n[[Category:Internet activism]]\n", "name_user": "QRep2020", "label": "safe", "comment": "Removed section header by accident.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/TSLAQ"}
{"title_page": "Stephen Jimenez", "text_new": "'''Stephen Jimenez''' is an American journalist, TV producer and author of ''[[The Book of Matt]]''.\n\n==Personal life==\nJimenez, who is gay,<ref>{{cite news |last1=RACHEL MARTIN |title='Book Of Matt': An Alternative Motive Behind The Infamous Murder |url=https://www.npr.org/2013/10/06/226438148/book-of-matt-the-real-motive-behind-an-infamous-murder?t=1540713250987 |accessdate=28 October 2018 |work=National Public Radio - NPR |date=6 October 2013 |quote=MARTIN: As a gay man, did you have any concerns that your reporting, that digging into this issue, would somehow diminish the power that the Shepard story had; and what it has meant for gay rights in this country?}}</ref> came out in the 1970's.  He marched in the first [[National March on Washington for Lesbian and Gay Rights]], which took place in 1979.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Herzog |first1=Katie |title=Matthew Shepard Is the World's Most Famous Gay Hate Crime Victim. But Was He Really Killed for Being Gay? |url=https://www.thestranger.com/slog/2018/10/26/34543412/matthew-shepard-is-the-worlds-most-famous-gay-hate-crime-victim-but-was-he-really-killed-for-being-gay |accessdate=28 October 2018 |work=[[The Stranger (newspaper)|The Stranger]] |quote=a gay man who came out in the 1970s, marched in the first National Gay March on Washington, and then survived the plague years of the AIDS epidemic}}</ref> He is a graduate of Georgetown University.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Joshua Rhett Miller |title=Matthew Shepard not murdered for being gay, new book claims |url=https://www.foxnews.com/us/matthew-shepard-not-murdered-for-being-gay-new-book-claims |accessdate=28 October 2018 |work=Fox News |date=22 November 2015 |quote=Jimenez, a veteran journalist, producer and graduate of Georgetown University}}</ref><ref>http://www.stephenjimenez.net/about.html</ref> He lives in Brooklyn and Santa Fe, NM.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Peyser |first1=Andrea |title=\u2018Uncomfortable truth\u2019 in Matthew Shepard\u2019s death |url=https://nypost.com/2013/10/28/uncomfortable-truth-behind-matthew-shepards-death/ |accessdate=28 October 2018 |work=[[New York Post]] |date=28 October 2013 |quote=Jimenez, 60, a Brooklyn native who splits his time between New York and Santa Fe, NM}}</ref>  Jimenez is also known as Steve Jimenez.<ref>{{cite news |last1=STEVE JIMENEZ |title=Book of Matt Author Responds to Media Matters |url=https://www.out.com/news-opinion/2014/11/24/book-matt-author-responds-media-matters-steve-jimenez |accessdate=28 October 2018 |work=[[Out (magazine)|Out]] |date=24 November 2018 |quote=\"BY STEVE JIMENEZ\"}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and Recognition==\nIn 2006, Jimenez won that year's Writers Guild Award for Analysis, Feature or Commentary, together with Richard Gerdau and Glenn Silber, for the ABC report \"The Matthew Shepherd Story; Secrets of a Murder (20/20)\".<ref>{{cite web |title=Previous Awards Winners: 2012-2006 |url=http://awards.wga.org/wga-awards/previous-nominees-winners-2012-2006 |website=The Writers Guild Awards |publisher=Writers Guild of America West |quote=(TV) NEWS SCRIPT \u2014 ANALYSIS, FEATURE, OR COMMENTARY  THE MATTHEW SHEPARD STORY: SECRETS OF A MURDER (20/20), Written by Richard Gerdau, Stephen Jimenez, Glenn Silber; ABC}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Dave McNary |title=Scribe tribe rides with kudo favorites |url=https://variety.com/2006/film/awards/scribe-tribe-rides-with-kudo-favorites-1117937424/ |accessdate=29 October 2018 |work=Variety |date=4 February 2006 |quote=(TV) NEWS SCRIPT \u2014 ANALYSIS, FEATURE, OR COMMENTARY \u201cThe Mattew Shepard Story: Secrets of a Murder\u201d (\u201c20/20\u201d) Written by Richard Gerdau, Stephen Jimenez, Glenn Silber; ABC}}</ref> In 2005, he shared with Silber and with Elizabeth Vargas a Mongerson Prize for Investigative Reporting on the News Award of Distinction from the [[Medill School of Journalism]] for work done for [[20/20 (U.S. TV program)|ABC's 20/20]].<ref>{{cite news |title=MEDILL AWARDS HIGHLIGHT COVERAGE OF DARFUR VIOLENCE, WMD STORY |url=https://www.northwestern.edu/newscenter/stories/2005/04/medill.html |accessdate=28 October 2018 |work=News - Northwestern Now |publisher=Northwestern University - Medill School of Journalism |date=26 April 2005 |quote=Medill also named three winners of the $1,000 Awards of Distinction -- Jonathan Landay and Tish Wells of Knight Ridder Newspapers; Pete Slover of The Dallas Morning News; and Stephen Jimenez, Glenn Silber and Elizabeth Vargas of ABC\u2019s \u201c20/20.\u201d}}</ref> He is an alumnus of the Film Residency at the [[Ucross Foundation]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Residency Program - Film |url=http://www.ucrossfoundation.org/residency-program/alumni-list/film/ |website=Ucross Foundation |publisher=Ucross Foundation |accessdate=28 October 2018 |quote=Film [...] Steve Jimenez}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nJimenez directed and produced for [[WTXF-TV]] the 1995 documentary ''Yearbook: The Class of '65'', documenting [[Edison/Fareira High School#Original Edison High School building|Philadelphia's Thomas Edison High School]] graduating class of 1965, which is believed to have suffered an unusually high number of casualties in the Vietnam war.<ref>{{cite news |last1=David Hiltbrand |title=Unexpected twists in a notorious murder case |url=http://www.philly.com/philly/columnists/david_hiltbrand/20140311_Unexpected_twists_in_a_notorious_murder_case.html |accessdate=29 October 2018 |work=[[The Philadelphia Inquirer]] |date=11 March 2014 |quote=Jimenez moved to Philadelphia in 1995, where he directed and produced the acclaimed documentary Yearbook: The Class of '65 for Fox29.  The film looked at the graduates of Thomas Edison High School in North Philadelphia, who suffered a devastating number of fatalities in the Vietnam War.  \"That was a career turning point for me,\" says Jimenez, who now splits his time between Brooklyn and Santa Fe, N.M. \"It was an opportunity to tell a powerful story with very little editorial interference and to learn firsthand about the Vietnam War from the families in Philadelphia who lost sons in the war.\"}}</ref>\n\nHe is a co-founder of the advocacy group ''New Yorkers Against Hidden Predators''.  The group seeks for the \"Child Victims Act\" to be passed<ref>{{cite news |title=Survivor Of Child Sexual Abuse On Challenges For Victims To Speak Out |url=http://www.ny1.com/nyc/all-boroughs/shows/2018/04/15/survivor-of-child-sexual-abuse-talks-about-challenges-for-victims-come-forward |accessdate=28 October 2018 |work=[[NY1]] |date=15 April 2018 |quote=the co-founder of advocacy group New Yorkers Against Hidden Predators [...] his more-than-decade-long fight for the Child Victims Act to protect children by forcing predators into the open.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=About Us |url=https://stophiddenpredators.org |website=New Yorkers Against Hidden Predators |publisher=New Yorkers Against Hidden Predators |accessdate=28 October 2018 |quote=New Yorkers Against Hidden Predators (NYAHP) is committed to passing the Child Victims Act in New York [...] NYAHP is seeking to reform New York State's antiquated child sexual abuse laws and bring to justice the hidden sexual predators that live in our communities today.}}</ref> which Jimenez has promoted for over ten years.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Elizabeth A. Harris |title=A New Push to Expand New York\u2019s Childhood Sexual Assault Law |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/12/06/nyregion/new-campaign-to-change-new-york-sex-assault-law-is-building.html |accessdate=28 October 2018 |work=The New York Times |date=6 December 2017 |quote=Stephen Jimenez, an abuse survivor who has been advocating for the bill for more than 10 years.}}</ref>\n\nJimenez is a trustee of the Ucross Foundation.<ref>{{cite web |title=UCROSS FOUNDATION WELCOMES THREE NEW MEMBERS TO THE BOARD OF TRUSTEES |url=http://www.ucrossfoundation.org/news/?article=92 |website=Ucross Foundation |publisher=[[Ucross Foundation]] |accessdate=28 October 2018 |date=6 August 2018 |quote=The full Ucross board of trustees also includes [...] Steve Jimenez (Santa Fe, NM)}}</ref>\n\nHe has written for [[Daily Beast]], Medium, the [[New York Post]], [[Byliner]] and [[Out (magazine)|Out]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Adnum |first1=Mark |title=Matthew Shepard and the gatekeepers of the gay orthodoxy |url=https://www.spiked-online.com/2015/03/06/matthew-shepard-and-the-gatekeepers-of-the-gay-orthodoxy/16678/ |accessdate=28 October 2018 |work=[[Spiked (magazine)|Spiked]] |date=6 March 2015 |quote=His work has been published by the Daily Beast, Medium, the New York Post, Byliner and Out.}}</ref>\n\n==The Book of Matt==\n\nIn 2013 Jimenez published ''The Book of Matt,'' an analysis of the murder of [[Matthew Shepard|Matthew Shephard]].  Jimenez first visited Laramie shortly after the murder, planning to write a screenplay and believing that the murder was a straightforward homophobic killing.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bindel |first1=Julie |title=The truth behind America\u2019s most famous gay-hate murder |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/oct/26/the-truth-behind-americas-most-famous-gay-hate-murder-matthew-shepard |accessdate=28 October 2018 |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=26 October 2014 |quote=Jimenez had no intention of causing such controversy. He\u2019s an award-winning writer and TV producer, and visited Laramie shortly after the murder to gather material for a screenplay about the case. When he started he was convinced that Matthew died at the hands of homophobes, but he soon discovered that Matthew\u2019s tragedy began long before the night he was killed.}}</ref> Jimenez spent 13 years researching the murder, and came to the conclusion that Matthew and one of the men convicted of his murder were involved in the illegal trade in [[Methamphetamine|crystal meth]].<ref name=\"MartinInterview\">{{cite news |last1=Martin |first1=Rachel |title='Book Of Matt': An Alternative Motive Behind The Infamous Murder (interview) |url=https://www.npr.org/2013/10/06/226438148/book-of-matt-the-real-motive-behind-an-infamous-murder |accessdate=29 October 2018 |publisher=[[National Public Radio]] |date=6 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Andrea Peyser |title=\u2018Uncomfortable truth\u2019 in Matthew Shepard\u2019s death |url=https://nypost.com/2013/10/28/uncomfortable-truth-behind-matthew-shepards-death/ |accessdate=28 October 2018 |work=New York Post |date=28 October 2013 |quote=After some 13 years of digging, including interviews with more than 100 sources, including Shepard\u2019s killers, Jimenez makes a radioactive suggestion}}</ref>\nJimenez has said his motivation for writing the book as a desire to show that \"the popular narrative (of homophobic murder) served a purpose, but it\u2019s only one thread of a bigger, richer, more challenging story whose lessons we have barely learned. To avoid topics of addiction, including how crystal meth ravaged the queer community (and Matt\u2019s life), is not helpful to anyone.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Katie Herzog |title=Matthew Shepard Is the World's Most Famous Gay Hate Crime Victim. But Was He Really Killed for Being Gay? |url=https://www.thestranger.com/slog/2018/10/26/34543412/matthew-shepard-is-the-worlds-most-famous-gay-hate-crime-victim-but-was-he-really-killed-for-being-gay |accessdate=28 October 2018 |work=The Stranger |date=26 October 2018 |quote=\"Yes, the popular narrative served a purpose, but it\u2019s only ONE thread of a bigger, richer, more challenging story whose lessons we have barely learned. To avoid topics of addiction, including how crystal meth ravaged the queer community (and Matt\u2019s life), is not helpful to anyone.\"}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jimenez, Stephen}}\n[[Category:American male journalists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Georgetown University alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:LGBT journalists from the United States]]\n[[Category:Gay writers]]\n[[Category:Television producers from New York City]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "'''Stephen Jimenez''' is an American journalist, TV producer and author of ''[[The Book of Matt]]''.\n\n==Personal life==\nJimenez, who is gay,<ref>{{cite news |last1=RACHEL MARTIN |title='Book Of Matt': An Alternative Motive Behind The Infamous Murder |url=https://www.npr.org/2013/10/06/226438148/book-of-matt-the-real-motive-behind-an-infamous-murder?t=1540713250987 |accessdate=28 October 2018 |work=National Public Radio - NPR |date=6 October 2013 |quote=MARTIN: As a gay man, did you have any concerns that your reporting, that digging into this issue, would somehow diminish the power that the Shepard story had; and what it has meant for gay rights in this country?}}</ref> came out in the 1970's.  He marched in the first [[National March on Washington for Lesbian and Gay Rights]], which took place in 1979.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Herzog |first1=Katie |title=Matthew Shepard Is the World's Most Famous Gay Hate Crime Victim. But Was He Really Killed for Being Gay? |url=https://www.thestranger.com/slog/2018/10/26/34543412/matthew-shepard-is-the-worlds-most-famous-gay-hate-crime-victim-but-was-he-really-killed-for-being-gay |accessdate=28 October 2018 |work=[[The Stranger (newspaper)|The Stranger]] |quote=a gay man who came out in the 1970s, marched in the first National Gay March on Washington, and then survived the plague years of the AIDS epidemic}}</ref> He is a graduate of Georgetown University.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Joshua Rhett Miller |title=Matthew Shepard not murdered for being gay, new book claims |url=https://www.foxnews.com/us/matthew-shepard-not-murdered-for-being-gay-new-book-claims |accessdate=28 October 2018 |work=Fox News |date=22 November 2015 |quote=Jimenez, a veteran journalist, producer and graduate of Georgetown University}}</ref><ref>http://www.stephenjimenez.net/about.html</ref> He lives in Brooklyn and Santa Fe, NM.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Peyser |first1=Andrea |title=\u2018Uncomfortable truth\u2019 in Matthew Shepard\u2019s death |url=https://nypost.com/2013/10/28/uncomfortable-truth-behind-matthew-shepards-death/ |accessdate=28 October 2018 |work=[[New York Post]] |date=28 October 2013 |quote=Jimenez, 60, a Brooklyn native who splits his time between New York and Santa Fe, NM}}</ref>  Jimenez is also known as Steve Jimenez.<ref>{{cite news |last1=STEVE JIMENEZ |title=Book of Matt Author Responds to Media Matters |url=https://www.out.com/news-opinion/2014/11/24/book-matt-author-responds-media-matters-steve-jimenez |accessdate=28 October 2018 |work=[[Out (magazine)|Out]] |date=24 November 2018 |quote=\"BY STEVE JIMENEZ\"}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and Recognition==\nIn 2006, Jimenez won that year's Writers Guild Award for Analysis, Feature or Commentary, together with Richard Gerdau and Glenn Silber, for the ABC report \"The Matthew Shepherd Story; Secrets of a Murder (20/20)\".<ref>{{cite web |title=Previous Awards Winners: 2012-2006 |url=http://awards.wga.org/wga-awards/previous-nominees-winners-2012-2006 |website=The Writers Guild Awards |publisher=Writers Guild of America West |quote=(TV) NEWS SCRIPT \u2014 ANALYSIS, FEATURE, OR COMMENTARY  THE MATTHEW SHEPARD STORY: SECRETS OF A MURDER (20/20), Written by Richard Gerdau, Stephen Jimenez, Glenn Silber; ABC}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Dave McNary |title=Scribe tribe rides with kudo favorites |url=https://variety.com/2006/film/awards/scribe-tribe-rides-with-kudo-favorites-1117937424/ |accessdate=29 October 2018 |work=Variety |date=4 February 2006 |quote=(TV) NEWS SCRIPT \u2014 ANALYSIS, FEATURE, OR COMMENTARY \u201cThe Mattew Shepard Story: Secrets of a Murder\u201d (\u201c20/20\u201d) Written by Richard Gerdau, Stephen Jimenez, Glenn Silber; ABC}}</ref> In 2005, he shared with Silber and with Elizabeth Vargas a Mongerson Prize for Investigative Reporting on the News Award of Distinction from the [[Medill School of Journalism]] for work done for [[20/20 (U.S. TV program)|ABC's 20/20]].<ref>{{cite news |title=MEDILL AWARDS HIGHLIGHT COVERAGE OF DARFUR VIOLENCE, WMD STORY |url=https://www.northwestern.edu/newscenter/stories/2005/04/medill.html |accessdate=28 October 2018 |work=News - Northwestern Now |publisher=Northwestern University - Medill School of Journalism |date=26 April 2005 |quote=Medill also named three winners of the $1,000 Awards of Distinction -- Jonathan Landay and Tish Wells of Knight Ridder Newspapers; Pete Slover of The Dallas Morning News; and Stephen Jimenez, Glenn Silber and Elizabeth Vargas of ABC\u2019s \u201c20/20.\u201d}}</ref> He is an alumnus of the Film Residency at the [[Ucross Foundation]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Residency Program - Film |url=http://www.ucrossfoundation.org/residency-program/alumni-list/film/ |website=Ucross Foundation |publisher=Ucross Foundation |accessdate=28 October 2018 |quote=Film [...] Steve Jimenez}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nJimenez directed and produced for [[WTXF-TV]] the 1995 documentary ''Yearbook: The Class of '65'', documenting [[Edison/Fareira High School#Original Edison High School building|Philadelphia's Thomas Edison High School]] graduating class of 1965, which is believed to have suffered an unusually high number of casualties in the Vietnam war.<ref>{{cite news |last1=David Hiltbrand |title=Unexpected twists in a notorious murder case |url=http://www.philly.com/philly/columnists/david_hiltbrand/20140311_Unexpected_twists_in_a_notorious_murder_case.html |accessdate=29 October 2018 |work=[[The Philadelphia Inquirer]] |date=11 March 2014 |quote=Jimenez moved to Philadelphia in 1995, where he directed and produced the acclaimed documentary Yearbook: The Class of '65 for Fox29.  The film looked at the graduates of Thomas Edison High School in North Philadelphia, who suffered a devastating number of fatalities in the Vietnam War.  \"That was a career turning point for me,\" says Jimenez, who now splits his time between Brooklyn and Santa Fe, N.M. \"It was an opportunity to tell a powerful story with very little editorial interference and to learn firsthand about the Vietnam War from the families in Philadelphia who lost sons in the war.\"}}</ref>\n\nHe is a co-founder of the advocacy group ''New Yorkers Against Hidden Predators''.  The group seeks for the \"Child Victims Act\" to be passed<ref>{{cite news |title=Survivor Of Child Sexual Abuse On Challenges For Victims To Speak Out |url=http://www.ny1.com/nyc/all-boroughs/shows/2018/04/15/survivor-of-child-sexual-abuse-talks-about-challenges-for-victims-come-forward |accessdate=28 October 2018 |work=[[NY1]] |date=15 April 2018 |quote=the co-founder of advocacy group New Yorkers Against Hidden Predators [...] his more-than-decade-long fight for the Child Victims Act to protect children by forcing predators into the open.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=About Us |url=https://stophiddenpredators.org |website=New Yorkers Against Hidden Predators |publisher=New Yorkers Against Hidden Predators |accessdate=28 October 2018 |quote=New Yorkers Against Hidden Predators (NYAHP) is committed to passing the Child Victims Act in New York [...] NYAHP is seeking to reform New York State's antiquated child sexual abuse laws and bring to justice the hidden sexual predators that live in our communities today.}}</ref> which Jimenez has promoted for over ten years.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Elizabeth A. Harris |title=A New Push to Expand New York\u2019s Childhood Sexual Assault Law |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/12/06/nyregion/new-campaign-to-change-new-york-sex-assault-law-is-building.html |accessdate=28 October 2018 |work=The New York Times |date=6 December 2017 |quote=Stephen Jimenez, an abuse survivor who has been advocating for the bill for more than 10 years.}}</ref>\n\nJimenez is a trustee of the Ucross Foundation.<ref>{{cite web |title=UCROSS FOUNDATION WELCOMES THREE NEW MEMBERS TO THE BOARD OF TRUSTEES |url=http://www.ucrossfoundation.org/news/?article=92 |website=Ucross Foundation |publisher=[[Ucross Foundation]] |accessdate=28 October 2018 |date=6 August 2018 |quote=The full Ucross board of trustees also includes [...] Steve Jimenez (Santa Fe, NM)}}</ref>\n\nHe has written for [[Daily Beast]], Medium, the [[New York Post]], [[Byliner]] and [[Out (magazine)|Out]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Adnum |first1=Mark |title=Matthew Shepard and the gatekeepers of the gay orthodoxy |url=https://www.spiked-online.com/2015/03/06/matthew-shepard-and-the-gatekeepers-of-the-gay-orthodoxy/16678/ |accessdate=28 October 2018 |work=[[Spiked (magazine)|Spiked]] |date=6 March 2015 |quote=His work has been published by the Daily Beast, Medium, the New York Post, Byliner and Out.}}</ref>\n\n==The Book of Matt==\n\nIn 2013 Jimenez published ''The Book of Matt,'' an analysis of the murder of [[Matthew Shepard|Matthew Shephard]].  Jimenez first visited Laramie shortly after the murder, planning to write a screenplay and believing that the murder was a straightforward homophobic killing.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bindel |first1=Julie |title=The truth behind America\u2019s most famous gay-hate murder |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/oct/26/the-truth-behind-americas-most-famous-gay-hate-murder-matthew-shepard |accessdate=28 October 2018 |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=26 October 2014 |quote=Jimenez had no intention of causing such controversy. He\u2019s an award-winning writer and TV producer, and visited Laramie shortly after the murder to gather material for a screenplay about the case. When he started he was convinced that Matthew died at the hands of homophobes, but he soon discovered that Matthew\u2019s tragedy began long before the night he was killed.}}</ref> Jimenez spent 13 years researching the murder, and came to the conclusion that Matthew and one of the men convicted of his murder were involved in the illegal trade in [[Methamphetamine|crystal meth]].<ref name=\"MartinInterview\">{{cite news |last1=Martin |first1=Rachel |title='Book Of Matt': An Alternative Motive Behind The Infamous Murder (interview) |url=https://www.npr.org/2013/10/06/226438148/book-of-matt-the-real-motive-behind-an-infamous-murder |accessdate=29 October 2018 |publisher=[[National Public Radio]] |date=6 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Andrea Peyser |title=\u2018Uncomfortable truth\u2019 in Matthew Shepard\u2019s death |url=https://nypost.com/2013/10/28/uncomfortable-truth-behind-matthew-shepards-death/ |accessdate=28 October 2018 |work=New York Post |date=28 October 2013 |quote=After some 13 years of digging, including interviews with more than 100 sources, including Shepard\u2019s killers, Jimenez makes a radioactive suggestion}}</ref>\nJimenez has said his motivation for writing the book as a desire to show that \"the popular narrative (of homophobic murder) served a purpose, but it\u2019s only one thread of a bigger, richer, more challenging story whose lessons we have barely learned. To avoid topics of addiction, including how crystal meth ravaged the queer community (and Matt\u2019s life), is not helpful to anyone.\"<ref>{{cite news |last1=Katie Herzog |title=Matthew Shepard Is the World's Most Famous Gay Hate Crime Victim. But Was He Really Killed for Being Gay? |url=https://www.thestranger.com/slog/2018/10/26/34543412/matthew-shepard-is-the-worlds-most-famous-gay-hate-crime-victim-but-was-he-really-killed-for-being-gay |accessdate=28 October 2018 |work=The Stranger |date=26 October 2018 |quote=\"Yes, the popular narrative served a purpose, but it\u2019s only ONE thread of a bigger, richer, more challenging story whose lessons we have barely learned. To avoid topics of addiction, including how crystal meth ravaged the queer community (and Matt\u2019s life), is not helpful to anyone.\"}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jimenez, Stephen}}\n[[Category:American male journalists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Georgetown University alumni]]\n[[Category:People from Brooklyn]]\n